00:12:06.750 --> 00:12:09.099
Let's look at the numbers here.
We had 15,20,

00:12:09.099 --> 00:12:13.250
then this one,
up to 20,25 and so on.

00:12:13.250 --> 00:12:20.049
So what's the pattern here?
Yes, Steven again.

00:12:20.049 --> 00:12:22.423
Student: If your
opponent doesn't choose 1 or 2,

00:12:22.423 --> 00:12:25.016
then you're always going to be
5% better off if you choose 2

00:12:25.016 --> 00:12:26.538
than 1.
Professor Ben Polak:

00:12:26.538 --> 00:12:28.923
Exactly, so ignoring these first
two positions which were a bit

00:12:28.923 --> 00:12:30.922
weird,
choosing 2 always gave me 5%

00:12:30.922 --> 00:12:34.167
more votes than choosing 1,
regardless of what the other

00:12:34.167 --> 00:12:36.273
person chooses.
So I mean if you want,

00:12:36.273 --> 00:12:38.693
you can fill in the
next--whatever it is--the next 6

00:12:38.693 --> 00:12:41.011
positions and see.
But you'll see that very

00:12:41.011 --> 00:12:44.260
clearly that Steven's right:
that choosing 2 will always get

00:12:44.260 --> 00:12:47.620
me 5% more of the votes than
choosing 1 from here on down.

00:12:47.620 --> 00:12:49.569
And in fact,
they'll go up in intervals of

00:12:49.569 --> 00:12:51.120
5.
So, in fact,

00:12:51.120 --> 00:12:57.466
it is true, it is in fact true,
so we can conclude that 2

00:12:57.466 --> 00:13:03.543
dominates--in fact,
we can do a bit better than

00:13:03.543 --> 00:13:08.720
that--we can say strictly
dominates 1.

00:13:08.720 --> 00:13:14.303
2 strictly dominates 1.
Is anything else dominated

00:13:14.303 --> 00:13:16.919
here, Steven already told us
that 10 is dominated.

00:13:16.919 --> 00:13:17.879
I'm not going to go through
that argument.

00:13:17.879 --> 00:13:19.620
Can everyone see that is
symmetric?

00:13:19.620 --> 00:13:22.251
Hang on a second,
