00:40:40.050 --> 00:40:54.909
To kick this off,
let's look at an example.

00:40:54.909 --> 00:40:56.906
So here's a game,
a very simple game with two

00:40:56.906 --> 00:40:58.829
players.
Player I is choosing Up,

00:40:58.829 --> 00:41:02.215
Middle, or Down.
And Player II is choosing Left

00:41:02.215 --> 00:41:05.500
or Right, and the payoffs are as
follows.

00:41:05.500 --> 00:41:06.960
They're nothing very
interesting.

00:41:06.960 --> 00:41:12.325
They're just numbers thought up
for the purpose:

00:41:12.325 --> 00:41:16.964
(4,2) and (2,3).
So we've got (5,1),

00:41:16.964 --> 00:41:20.501
(0,2), (1,3),
(4,1), (4,2),

00:41:20.501 --> 00:41:23.551
and (2,3).
So, first of all,

00:41:23.551 --> 00:41:28.302
let's try and analyze this game
using the tools we've learned so

00:41:28.302 --> 00:41:33.426
far.
So does either player have a

00:41:33.426 --> 00:41:38.550
dominated strategy?
Any takers?

00:41:38.550 --> 00:41:41.552
So I claim that neither player
has a dominated strategy,

00:41:41.552 --> 00:41:44.098
let's just check.
So, for example,

00:41:44.098 --> 00:41:49.188
you might think Down is
dominated, but if we look a bit

00:41:49.188 --> 00:41:54.278
carefully we see that Down
actually does better than Up

00:41:54.278 --> 00:41:58.901
against Right,
and Down does better than

00:41:58.901 --> 00:42:03.012
Middle against Left.
Similarly, we can see that

00:42:03.012 --> 00:42:06.544
Right is not dominated,
because it does better against

00:42:06.544 --> 00:42:09.122
Up, than does Left.
But Left isn't dominated

00:42:09.122 --> 00:42:11.950
because it does better against
Middle than does Right …

00:42:11.950 --> 00:42:14.346
so on and so forth.
You can work through this game

00:42:14.346 --> 00:42:17.099
and you can check pretty quickly
that nothing is dominated.

00:42:17.099 --> 00:42:21.441
So if the only tool I taught
you in this class was dominated

00:42:21.441 --> 00:42:25.855
strategies and the iterative
deletion of dominated strategies

00:42:25.855 --> 00:42:28.524
